/PG798/XX/PR
/IT(Creation)/XX/PR
/PR
He doesnÚt know the world at all/PR
Who stays in his nest and doesnÚt go out./PR
He doesnÚt know what birds know best/PR
Nor what I want to sing about,/PR
That the world is full of loveliness./PR
/PR
When dewdrops sparkle in the grass/PR
And earthÚs aflood with morning light,/PR
A blackbird sings upon a bush/PR
To greet the dawning after night./PR
Then I know how fine it is to live./PR
/PR
Hey, try to open up your heart/PR
To beauty; go to the woods someday/PR
And weave a wreath of memory there./PR
Then if the tears obscure your way/PR
YouÚll know how wonderful it is/PR
To be alive./PR
An anonymous child in the/PR
Terezin Concentration Camp, 1941/XX/PR
We give away our thanks/PR
to the earth,/PR
which gives us our home./PR
We give away our thanks/PR
to the rivers and lakes and oceans,/PR
which give away their water./PR
We give away our thanks/PR
to the trees,/PR
which give away fruit and nuts./PR
We give away our thanks/PR
to the wind,/PR
which brings rain to water the plants./PR
We give away our thanks/PR
to the sun,/PR
which gives away warmth and light./PI/PR
/PR
/PR
/PR
/PL799/XX/PR
All beings on earth--the trees, the/PR
animals, the wind and the rivers--/PR
give away to one another--/PR
So all is in balance./PR
We give away our promise to begin/PR
to learn/PR
how to stay in balance--/PR
with all the earth./PR
A Native American Prayer/XX/PR
/KAGodÚs Wheel/XX/PR
God says to me with kind of a smile,/PR
"Hey how would you like to be God awhile/PR
And steer the world?"/PR
"Okay," says I, "IÚll give it a try./PR
Where do I set?/PR
How much do I get?/PR
What time is lunch?/PR
When can I quit?"/PR
"Gimme back that wheel," says God,/PR
"I donÚt think youÚre quite ready yet."/PR
Shel Silverstein/XX/PR
/PR
O our Mother the Earth, O our Father the Sky,/PR
Your children are we, and with tired backs/PR
We bring you the gifts you love./PR
Then weave for us a garment of brightness;/PR
May the warp be the white light of morning,/PR
May the weft be the red light of evening,/PR
May the fringes be the falling rain,/PR
May the border be the standing rainbow./PR
Thus weave for us a garment of brightness,/PR
That we may walk fittingly where birds sing,/PR
That we may walk fittingly where grass is green,/PR
O our Mother the Earth, O our Father the Sky./PR
Tewa (Native American)/XX/PR
