/PL809/XXREADINGS: SUKKOT/XX/PR
/KAFeast of Booths/XX/PR
This was the season of our ancestorsÚ joy:/PR
not only when they gathered grapes and the/PR
fruit of trees/PR
in Israel, but when, locked in the dark and/PR
stony streets/PR
they held--symbols of a life from which they/PR
were banished/PR
but to which they would surely return--/PR
the branches of palm trees and of willows, the/PR
twigs of the myrtle,/PR
and the bright odorous citrons./PR
/PR
This was the grove of palms with its deep well/PR
in the stony ghetto in the blaze of noon;/PR
this is the living stream lined with willows;/PR
and this the thick-leaved myrtles and trees/PR
heavy with fruit/PR
in the barren ghetto--a garden/PR
where the unjustly hated were justly safe at last./PR
/PR
In booths this week of holiday/PR
as those who gathered grapes in Israel lived/PR
and also to remember we were cared for/PR
in the wilderness--/PR
I remember how frail my present dwelling is/PR
even if of stones and steel./PR
/PR
I know this is the season of our joy:/PR
we have completed the readings of the Torah/PR
and we begin again;/PR
but I remember how slowly I have learnt,/PR
how little,/PR
how fast the year went by, the years--/PR
how few./PR
Charles Reznikoff/XX/PR
